{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583723"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:26:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:26:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12801"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12801"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67796"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5242"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"595"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2968"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22701"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a two day history of increasing pain in her left breast pain. She has a three month old daughter and she is actively breastfeeding. The pain is now limiting her from feeding through her left breast. On examination her pulse is 90/min, blood pressure 110/76 mmHg and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is an area of redness and tenderness on the outer aspect of her left breast.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely causative organism for her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus species","Candida albicans","Staphylococcus aureus","Staphylococcus epidermidis","Lactobacillus species"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has lactation mastitis and this occurs in about 10% of breastfeeding women. The most common causative organism for mastitis is \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a bacteria found on normal skin flora. In a breastfeeding mother, skin cracks around the nipple enable the bacteria to enter the breast tissue and cause an infection. Management of mastitis involves continuing to breast feed, using warm and cold compress, emptying the breast as much as possible during every feed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcis epidermidis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus species\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/strong\u003E are also causative organism for mastitis, but are not as common as staphylococcus aureus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactobacillus\u003C/strong\u003E is a probiotic that helps to promote gut health in children consuming breast milk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mastitis is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus"],"references":["https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/ccf54e89-7e44-409a-afa9-c14f1bb40639/Lactational-mastitis-and-breast-abscess.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12801"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T09:41